{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/itch-widespread/background-information/causes/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"5d85e75d-599f-583b-843d-861aeef9a901","slug":"causes","fullItemName":"Causes","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 8b3acf2c-c9ca-43d8-b10d-716dfa9e9e3a --><h2>What causes it?</h2><!-- end field 8b3acf2c-c9ca-43d8-b10d-716dfa9e9e3a -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item e6fe3dfd-6e0f-45b5-a2a8-751f927bace5 --><!-- begin field 91d326f1-6009-4ab2-8fea-0bc721ba97ec --><ul><li>The causes of widespread itch are not well understood, although histamine and other mediators (including neuropeptides, cytokines, and prostaglandins) have been implicated&nbsp;[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/itch-widespread/references/\">Davies, 2007</a>]. There are a variety of possible underlying causes, but sometimes no cause is identified [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/itch-widespread/references/\">BAD, 2013</a>].<ul><li><strong>Dry skin</strong>&nbsp;(xerosis). This is most common in older adults, and often occurs in the winter in cold climates [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/itch-widespread/references/\">Moses, 2003</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/itch-widespread/references/\">BAD, 2013</a>].</li><li><strong>Skin conditions</strong>. For more information, see the CKS topics on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/chickenpox/\">Chickenpox</a>, <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/eczema-atopic/\">Eczema - atopic</a>, <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/insect-bites-stings/\">Insect bites and stings</a>, <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/scabies/\">Scabies</a>, and <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/urticaria/\">Urticaria</a>.</li><li><strong>Systemic disease</strong> is identified in 10&ndash;50% of people with widespread itch [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/itch-widespread/references/\">Roebuck, 2006</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/itch-widespread/references/\">Davies, 2007</a>].<ul><li>Renal disease &mdash; around half of people with chronic kidney disease experience itch. This increases to around 80% of people on long-term renal dialysis [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/itch-widespread/references/\">Charlesworth and Bletrani, 2002</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/itch-widespread/references/\">Davies, 2007</a>]. For more information, see the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/chronic-kidney-disease/\">Chronic kidney disease - not diabetic</a>.</li><li>Liver disease &mdash; itch is usually secondary to cholestasis. For more information, see the CKS topics on&nbsp;<a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/jaundice-in-adults/\">Jaundice in adults</a>&nbsp;and <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/gallstones/\">Gallstones</a>.</li><li>Haematological &mdash; for example iron deficiency, polycythaemia vera, or haemochromatosis (rare).</li><li>Endocrine disorders &mdash; for example thyroid disorders (thyrotoxicosis causes itch more commonly than hypothyroidism).&nbsp;</li><li>Malignancy &mdash; for example Hodgkin&#39;s lymphoma, cutaneous T-cell lymphoma, leukaemia, and multiple myeloma.</li><li>Neurological &mdash; for example multiple sclerosis. For more information, see the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/multiple-sclerosis/\">Multiple sclerosis</a>.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Pregnancy</strong>&nbsp;(usually only in the latter stages) and postmenopausal hormonal changes. For more information see the CKS topics on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/itch-in-pregnancy/\">Itch in pregnancy</a>&nbsp;and <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/menopause/\">Menopause</a>.</li><li><strong>Drugs</strong> &mdash; most commonly opioids, but also statins, angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitors, digoxin, chloroquine, and sulphonamides.</li></ul><ul><li><strong>Psychological causes</strong> &mdash; for example psychogenic pruritus. Delusions of parasitosis may be associated with other psychological conditions such as depression or anxiety disorders.</li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/itch-widespread/references/\">Moses, 2003</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/itch-widespread/references/\">Greaves, 2004</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/itch-widespread/references/\">Davies, 2007</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/itch-widespread/references/\">Lynde et al, 2008</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/itch-widespread/references/\">Mollanazar, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/itch-widespread/references/\">Primary Care Dermatology Society, 2015</a>]</p><!-- end field 91d326f1-6009-4ab2-8fea-0bc721ba97ec --><!-- end item e6fe3dfd-6e0f-45b5-a2a8-751f927bace5 -->","topic":{"id":"98db983b-94d0-57fc-8f85-3c35dffdbc84","topicId":"3ff60e1b-3717-41cc-be12-1871b4284ba6","topicName":"Itch - widespread","slug":"itch-widespread","lastRevised":"Last revised in December 2016","chapters":[{"id":"c31a1ea7-3548-5767-9a55-10f56f4ea14a","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"316853c8-d1ca-5613-8c4d-c33ea7c0fd8b","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"64abf96